<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="374" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,333,1295]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,462,513,540]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The taxon belongs to 
<emphasis box="[714,951,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bory de St Vincent" authorityYear="1824" box="[714,820,513,539]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Colurella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" phylum="Rotifera" rank="genus">Colurella</taxonomicName>
uncinata—
</emphasis>
group on account of its relatively short and high lorica, and short toes, and appears closest to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ehrenberg, 1830)" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenberg" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[701,1179,549,576]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Colurella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" phylum="Rotifera" rank="subSpecies" species="uncinata" subSpecies="bicuspidata">
<emphasis box="[701,969,549,576]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">C. uncinata bicuspidata</emphasis>
(Ehrenberg, 1830)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1193,1291,549,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,497,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,481,1840]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Lepadellidae, line drawings. Figure 1a–b: Squatinella curviseta n. sp., a: habitus, lateral (scale bar: 100µm); b: detail of foot, lateral (scale bar: 50µm). Figure 2a–c: Squatinella longipila n. sp., habitus. a: detail, body (scale bar: 50µm); b–c: complete specimens (scale bar: 50µm). Figure 3a–c: Colurella asymmetrica n. sp. a: caudal region and foot, left; b: habitus, right; c: habitus, ventral view. Figure 4: Colurella uncinata bicuspidata: habitus, right (3, 4: scale bar: 50µm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3653634" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3653634/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">Figure 4</figureCitation>
). The animal is, however, readily distinguished by the asymmetrical posterior lorica and by the shape of the single caudal spine, which is not merely an extension of the ventral lorica margin, but is reinforced by a short ridge. By having an asymmetrical caudal spine the animal reminds of 
<taxonomicName authority="Carlin, 1939" authorityName="Carlin" authorityYear="1939" box="[659,927,657,684]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Colurella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="sinistra">
<emphasis box="[659,777,658,684]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">C. sinistra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Carlin, B" box="[786,927,657,683]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" pagination="1 - 68" refId="ref9371" refString="Carlin, B, (1939) Uber die Rotatorien einiger Seen bei Aneboda. Meddelanden Lunds Universitets Limnologiska Institution, 2, 1 - 68." type="journal article" year="1939">Carlin, 1939</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Wei et al., 2019" authorityName="Wei" authorityYear="2019" box="[985,1279,657,684]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Lepadella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis box="[985,1086,657,684]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">C. ovalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wei N. &amp; Jersabek, C. D. &amp; Xu, R. &amp; Yang, Y." box="[1094,1279,657,684]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" pagination="475 - 490" refId="ref11979" refString="Wei N., Jersabek, C. D., Xu, R. &amp; Yang, Y. (2019) New species and records of Colurella (Rotifera: Lepadellidae) from South China, with a key to Chinese Colurella. Zootaxa, 4586 (3), 475 - 490. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4586.3.5" type="journal article" year="2019">
Wei 
<emphasis box="[1147,1205,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">et al.</emphasis>
, 2019
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter species are larger, and are easily distinguished by their differently shaped lorica and caudal spine shape. The shape of the caudal spine in 
<taxonomicName authority="Luo &amp; Segers, 2020" authorityName="Luo &amp; Segers" authorityYear="2020" box="[393,568,730,756]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Colurella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="asymmetrica" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[393,568,730,756]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">C. asymmetrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[574,636,730,756]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[574,636,730,756]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is somewhat similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Wulfert, 1965" authorityName="Wulfert" authorityYear="1965" box="[976,1257,729,756]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Colurella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="collaris">
<emphasis box="[976,1093,729,756]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">C. collaris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wulfert, K." box="[1099,1257,729,756]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374" pagination="347 - 366" refId="ref12136" refString="Wulfert, K. (1965) Radertiere aus einigern afrikanishen Gewassern. Limnologica, Berlin, 3 (3), 347 - 366." type="journal article" year="1965">Wulfert, 1965</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but this species has a pronouncedly projecting and stippled head aperture margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,333,1295]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,463,801,828]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Parthenogenetic female (male unknown): Lorica relatively high (length: height &lt;1.7) and broad (height: width ca. 1.7). Anterior head aperture margins coincident, smoothly and evenly curved, ventrally a deep V-shaped, dorsally a shallower U-shaped sinus. Dorsal margin almost evenly curved, ventral margin straight, sulcus shallow. Foot aperture an inverted U-shape in ventral view, lateral margins protruded into asymmetrical projections: right projection relatively large, broad-based triangular with a terminal spinulet and reinforced by a longitudinal ridge of ca. one fourth of lorica length; left short, broad-based, triangular with a short longitudinal reinforcement ridge. Apertures to the lateral antennas situated relatively high and distally on the lorica. Foot with three short pseudosegments; terminal pseudosegment slightly longer than first and second, with a dorsal sensory groove basally. Toes short, straight, evenly narrowing from basis to pointed tip.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="374" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,333,1295]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,1126,1152]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">Measurements</emphasis>
(n=6). Lorica length: 75–80 (77); lorica width: 47–50 (49), lorica height: 48–50 (49); right caudal spine: 7–9 (7); left caudal spine: 2–4 (3); head aperture width: 4–11 (7); depth dorsally: 5–10 (7); depth ventrally: 26–30 (29); Foot aperture width: 11–13 (12); length: 21–26 (24); toe length: 12–18 (16).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="374" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,333,1295]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1234,1260]" pageId="3" pageNumber="374">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is an adjective, referring to the species’ most remarkable diagnostic feature, the asymmetrical caudal spines of the lorica.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
